Communicated by:
ProMED

[For those who wish to see the detailed global data, a snapshot of the Worldometer table at the time we accessed it is available at https://promedmail.org/wp-content/uploads/world-pdf/2022%20WORLDDATA%20JAN6_1641583094.pdf.

A 7-day series of cumulative data reported by countries, territories, and reporting entities can be found at https://promedmail.org/wp-content/uploads/world-pdf/2022%20JAN6WORLD7_1641583112.pdf.

In the past 24 hours, 28 countries including the USA (900 310), France (328 214), Spain (242 440), the UK (178 163), India (141 374), Argentina (110 533), Italy (108 297), Australia (98 686), Turkey (63 214), Brazil (54 900), Germany (59 393), Sweden (41 383), Portugal (38 734), Canada (34 919), the Netherlands (34 872), Greece (29 334), Belgium (27 282), Mexico (28 023), Switzerland (27 997), Columbia (26 190), Ireland (21 926), Philippines (21 747), Denmark (16 779), Viet Nam (16 278), Russia (16 735), Israel (14 745), Poland (11 901), and Bolivia (11 002) reported the highest numbers of cases, all reporting more than 10 000 newly confirmed cases. A global total of 7004 deaths were reported in the preceding 24 hours (late 5 Jan 2022 to late 6 Jan 2022). The exponential rise in cases over the last couple of weeks can be attributed to the rapid increase in the omicron variant cases in over 90 countries. Studies suggest that the omicron variant causes milder disease than the previously dominant delta variant, but the high number of cases caused by this highly infectious/transmissible variant could rapidly overwhelm hospitals and health systems. The 7-day averages indicate an increasing global trend on cases with some reduction in deaths.

A total of 75 countries reported more than 1000 cases in the past 24 hours; 43 of the 75 countries are from the European region, 8 are from the Americas region, 5 are from the Western Pacific region, 6 are from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 3 from the South East Asia region, and 10 are from the African region.

Comparing the 7-day averages of daily confirmed cases from the past 7 days and those from 8-14 days ago, case counts have increased by 66.4%, while daily reported deaths have increased by 0.49%. Similar comparative 7-day averages in the USA show a 75.9% increase in daily reported cases and a 23.9% increase in reported deaths.

Impression: The global daily reported over 2.9 million newly confirmed infections in the past 24 hours with over 303.78 million cumulative reported cases and over 5.49 million reported deaths. - Mod.UBA

